7 Nov 1373":"7 november 1373","1396":"1396","1351":"1351","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1338":"1338","1448":"1448","1379":"1379","1432":"1432","1342":"1342","1375":"1375","1409":"1409","about 1375":"circa 1375","Boarstall, Buckinghamshire, England":"Boarstall, Buckinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Chalgrove, Oxfordshire, England":"Chalgrove, Oxfordshire, England","Wallingford, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wallingford, Berkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1350–1396":"1350–1396","1351–1409":"1351–1409","1375–1432":"1375–1432","1379–Female":"1379–Deceased","–1448":"–1448","1338–Male":"1338–Deceased","1342–Female":"1342–Deceased","18 Oct 1380":"18 October 1380","7 Nov 1373":"7 November 1373","1396":"1396","1351":"1351","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1338":"1338","1448":"1448","1379":"1379","1432":"1432","1342":"1342","1375":"1375","1409":"1409","about 1375":"about 1375","Boarstall, Buckinghamshire, England":"Boarstall, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Chalgrove, Oxfordshire, England":"Chalgrove, Oxfordshire, England","Wallingford, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wallingford, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"James","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Welsh: from the Middle English personal name <i>James</i>. Introduced to England by the Normans, this is an Old French form of Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of Latin <i>Iacobus</i>, Greek <i>Iakōbos</i>, the New Testament rendering of Hebrew <i>Ya‘aqob</i> (see   Jacob  ). The medieval Latin (Vulgate) Bible distinguished between Old Testament <i>Iacob</i> (which was uninflected) and New Testament <i>Iacobus</i> (with inflections). The latter developed into <i>James</i> in medieval French. The distinction was carried over into the King James Bible of 1611, and   Jacob   and <i>James</i> remain as separate names in English usage. Most European languages, however, make no such distinction, so that forms such as French   Jacques  , stand for both the Old and the New Testament names. This surname is also very common among African Americans. Compare   Jack  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Giacomo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Domenico, Gino, Salvatore.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Giacomo</i>, from Latin <i>Jacobus</i> via Late Latin <i>Jacomus</i> (see   James   and   Jacob  )."]},{"name":"Jamie","meanings":["Scottish (mainly Angus): from a Scots pet form of the personal name   James  ."]},{"name":"Jemison","meanings":["English (northern): patronymic from the personal name <i>Jem</i> (a pet form of   James  ) + <i>son</i>. Compare   Jamison  ."]},{"name":"Jemmett","meanings":["English (southern): from the Middle English personal name <i>Jemet</i>, a diminutive of <i>Jem</i>, a pet form of   James  ."]},{"name":"Jaime","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Jesus, Jorge, Juan, Manuel, Carlos, Javier, Arturo, Luis, Alfredo, Enrique, Miguel.","Spanish: from the personal name <i>Jaime</i>, an equivalent of   James  ."]},{"name":"Jamison","meanings":["English and Scottish: from Middle English and Scots <i>Jami(e)son</i>, <i>Jameson</i>, <i>Jem(i)son</i> ‘son of <i>James</i>’ (see   James  ). <i>Jameson</i> and <i>Jamison</i> are mainly found in northern England, especially in Northumberland and Durham, while in Scotland the more usual form is   Jamieson  , but all three versions occur on either side of the border.","Scottish: variant of   McCamish  ."]},{"name":"Jacobo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Jesus, Francisco, Juan, Manuel, Miguel, Rafael, Alfredo, Luis, Carlos, Mario, Roberto.","Spanish and Italian: from the Latin personal name <i>Jacobus</i> (see   James  ,   Giacomo  )."]},{"name":"Jemmott","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Alicia, Armando, Dionicio, Gregoria, Guillermo, Roberto, Rosita, Ruperto.","English: from the personal name <i>Jemot</i>, a diminutive of <i>Jem</i>, a pet form of   James  . This surname is frequent in Barbados, Trinidad and Tobago, and Saint Lucia."]},{"name":"Como","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Sal, Salvatore, Giuseppe, Ignazio, Nunzio, Vito, Angelo, Antonio, Camillo, Carlo, Carmela, Caterina.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Como</i>, a short form of <i>Giacomo</i>, an equivalent of   James  .","Italian: habitational name from Como in Lombardy."]},{"name":"Jacob","meanings":["Jewish, English, Welsh, German, Portuguese, French (mainly Alsace and Lorraine), Walloon, Breton, Dutch, Flemish, Swedish, Danish, and Norwegian: derivative, via Latin <i>Jacob(us)</i>, from the Hebrew personal name <i>Ya‘aqob</i> (<i>Yaakov</i>). In the Bible, this is the name of the crafty younger twin brother of Esau (Genesis 25:26), who took advantage of the latter's hunger and impetuousness to persuade him to part with his birthright ‘for a mess of potage’. The name is traditionally interpreted as coming from Hebrew <i>akev</i> ‘heel’: Jacob is said to have been born holding on to Esau's heel. In English usage the name <i>Jacob</i> is regarded as distinct from the name   James  , but they are of identical origin. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, for example Assyrian/Chaldean or Arabic   Yaqub  ,   Yakub  ,   Yacoub  , or   Yacob  , Slovenian   Jakob   and <b>Jakop</b>, Czech and Slovak   Jakub  , and also their patronymics and other derivatives (see examples at   Jacobs   and   Jacobson  ). The name <i>Jacob</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Chacko  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   